- Review for accuracy
- Ensure completeness
- Get review if major changes

## Documentation Review

### Review Requirements
- Review documentation in PRs
- Verify accuracy
- Verify completeness
- Verify clarity
- Update if needed

### Documentation Checklist
- [ ] Accurate
- [ ] Complete
- [ ] Clear
- [ ] Up-to-date
- [ ] Well-organized
- [ ] Properly formatted

## Prohibited Practices

### NEVER:
- Leave documentation outdated
- Skip documentation updates
- Write unclear documentation
- Document implementation details in architecture docs
- Mix concerns in documentation

### ALWAYS:
- Keep documentation current
- Update when code changes
- Write clear documentation
- Organize documentation properly
- Review documentation

## Documentation Tools

### Markdown
- Use standard Markdown
- Use proper syntax
- Use code highlighting
- Use tables and lists

### Diagrams
- Use Mermaid for diagrams
- Keep diagrams simple
- Update diagrams when architecture changes
- Include diagrams in relevant docs

## Documentation Location Rules

### Root Documentation
- `README.md`: Project overview (keep in root)
- Architecture docs: Can be in root or `/docs`
- Status docs: Keep in root for visibility

### Organized Documentation
- Detailed guides: `/docs/guides/`
- API docs: `/docs/api/`
- Architecture details: `/docs/architecture/`
- Domain details: `/docs/domain/`

## Version Control

### Documentation in Git
- All documentation in version control
- Track changes to documentation
- Review documentation changes
- Keep documentation history

### Documentation Updates
- Commit documentation with code
- Update docs in same PR as code
- Don't commit docs separately unless docs-only change
